properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Traralgon Creek.

    Minor Flooding possible in the flood watch area from Wednesday afternoon 
    A mature low-pressure system located offshore of the New South Wales coast will remain near the coast until early Thursday, before moving eastwards across the Tasman Sea. 
    Moderate to heavy rainfall has been observed across the Gippsland area since Tuesday morning and further rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Wednesday and Thursday. River level rises have been observed in several catchments in Gippsland. 
    Further river level rises and areas of minor flooding are possible across the Flood Watch area from Wednesday afternoon. The location and severity of the flooding is extremely dependent on the movement of the low and the areas of heaviest rainfall.
    Catchments in the Flood Watch area are relatively wet following recent rainfall.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 03/07/2025 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact the National Relay Service and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Wongarra, 500m east of Carisbrook Falls.

  • Due to a whale carcass there could be an increase in shark activity reported at Wongarra, 500m east of Carisbrook Falls.
  • A whale carcass can attract sharks to the area and mean they are closer to the shore than normal.
  • While it is not uncommon for sharks to be present off the Victorian coast, you should exercise additional caution in the area.
Avoid the area. Stay informed and do not enter the water at closed beaches.
What you should do:

  • If you see sharks, report the sighting by calling Triple Zero (000) or notify lifesavers immediately if you are at a patrolled beach.
Staying safe at nearby beaches:
  • Always swim, dive or surf with a friend.
  • Swim between the red and yellow flags on patrolled beaches.
  • Don't swim in places where human or animal waste enters the water.
  • Keep away from large schools of fish, seals or other wildlife as these can attract sharks.
Impacts in your area:
  • The Victorian Fisheries Authority is assisting wildlife officers and park rangers with the management of a whale carcass.
This message was issued by Victorian Fisheries Authority.

The next update is expected by 07/07/2025 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.   
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Genoa River.

Moderate flooding occurring at The Gorge and possible at Weeragua overnight Wednesday into Thursday.

Moderate to heavy rainfall since Tuesday morning has caused river level rises across the East Gippsland river catchments. Further moderate to heavy rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Wednesday and Thursday.

Moderate flooding has developed along the Genoa River, where further rises are possible overnight Wednesday with forecast rainfall. Moderate flooding may develop along the Cann River at Weeragua overnight Wednesday, and river levels are steady near the minor flood level at Chandlers Creek. Further rises are possible across the catchments with forecast rain.

Genoa River:
Moderate flooding is likely along the Genoa River.

The Genoa River at The Gorge is currently at 2.21 m and steady, with moderate flooding. The Genoa River at The Gorge is likely to remain around the moderate flood level (2.20 m) overnight Wednesday into Thursday morning. Further rises are possible with forecast rain.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

Impacts in your area:
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides – be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 03/07/2025 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

Further river level rises and areas of minor flooding are possible across the Flood Watch area from Wednesday afternoon. The location and severity of the flooding is extremely dependent on the movement of the low and the areas of heaviest rainfall. 

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are relatively wet following recent rainfall. 


Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Cann River. 

Major flooding expected at Weeragua around midnight Wednesday into Thursday.

Moderate flooding occurring at Chandlers Creek and The Gorge.

Moderate to heavy rainfall since Tuesday morning has caused river level rises across the East Gippsland river catchments. Further moderate to heavy rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Wednesday and Thursday.

Major flooding is expected to develop along the Cann River at Weeragua, and moderate flooding has developed at Chandlers Creek. Further rises are possible overnight Wednesday into Thursday morning with forecast rainfall.

This situation is being closely monitored, and this warning will be updated as necessary.

Cann River:
Major flooding is expected along the Cann River.

The Cann River at Chandlers Creek is currently at 2.33 m and steady, with moderate flooding. The Cann River at Chandlers Creek is likely to remain above the moderate flood level (2.30 m) overnight Wednesday into Thursday. Further rises are possible with forecast rain.

The Cann River at Weeragua is currently at 3.97 m and rising, just below the major flood level (4.00 m). The Cann River at Weeragua is expected to exceed the major flood level (4.00 m) around 12:00 am Thursday. The river may remain above the major flood level (4.00 m) during Thursday morning.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

Impacts in your area:
  • A small number of properties are likely to be impacted opposite the Cann River Police station and in the vicinity of Humphreys Road.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides – be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 03/07/2025 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.
